"52.674316","longitude":"1.236496","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"131","title":"Hesley Wood Scout Activity centre","description":"South Yorkshire Scouts Site","contact":"0114 246 7912","link":"http:\/\/www.hesleywood.org\/index.html","lastupdated":"2011-09-19","latitude":"53.468987","longitude":"-1.460876","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"133","title":"MOOR HOUSE ADVENTURE CENTRE","description":"Scout Campsite with 15 acres of camping, 38 bed indoor accommodation, loads of professionally run activities. Full time staff. Open all year round. ","contact":"Graeme Popay - Centre Manager","link":"http:\/\/www.moor-house.org.uk ","lastupdated":"2011-09-20","latitude":"54.806171","longitude":"-1.512374","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"134","title":"Bibbys Farm scout campsite & activity centre","description":"scout camp site","contact":"tel\/fax: 01257 249391 email: bookingoffice@bibbysfarm.org ","link":"http:\/\/bibbysfarm.org\/new\/go.php?page=main","lastupdated":"2011-09-28","latitude":"53.646744","longitude":"-2.600664","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"135","title":"Fylde District Scout Headquarters","description":"Fylde Districts Scout headquarters new accomodation block opening summer 2012 with climbing wall, shooting, archery, activity barn, field and woods.","contact":"See web site","link":"http:\/\/www.fyldescouts.org.uk","lastupdated":"2012-03-31","latitude":"53.761189","longitude":"-3.007895","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"136","title":"Gradbach Scout Camp Site","description":"Remote site with plenty of space and friendly staff. ","contact":"Bookings@GradbachScoutCamp.org.uk\n","link":"http:\/\/www.gradbachscoutcamp.org.uk\/","lastupdated":"2011-10-10","latitude":"53.191386","longitude":"-2.008663","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"137","title":"Runways End Outdoor Centre","description":"Joint venture by Blackwater Valley Scouts and Hampshire CC","contact":"(see website)","link":"http:\/\/runwaysend.wordpress.com\/","lastupdated":"2011-10-12","latitude":"51.264807","longitude":"-0.770616","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"138","title":"Kingston Ridge","description":"Kingston Ridge Scout Campsite is just shy of 8 acres of fields and woodland, owned and managed by Basildon District Scouts. It is situated in the Langdon Hills area on the outskirts of Basildon in Essex, in a very quiet and rural setting. The surrounding open countryside and woodlands belong to Essex Wildlife Trust.\n\nOver the past couple of years it has been quietly and carefully redeveloped. A casual glance will suggest that nothing much has changed but look closer and you will find that there has been an enormous amount of work undertaken to greatly improve the facilities and resources of this lovely site.\n\nSignificant development work has taken place in a thoughtful and sensitive manner so as not to spoil the area. This means that we will have, from this season, resources and facilities to match the best sites. Yet one of the best features of this site is it\u2019s unspoiled nature. A lovely little oasis of peace and tranquility just two miles by road from the centre of one of the biggest towns in Essex.\n\nFacilities include Showers, toilets, archery and shooting range, aerial runway, assault course\/adventure playground and backwoods area.\n\nThe site has plenty of space for large events as well as individual small sites for patrols.\n\nPlease note, the site does not have electrical facilities - power can be provided by generator, hot water\/shower facilities are therefore by prior agreement & charge - please check booking form for details.","contact":"Ron Acton Tel: 07757 810891 or via bookings@kingstonridgecampsite.co.uk","link":"http:\/\/www.kingstonridgecampsite.co.uk\/","lastupdated":"2011-10-13","latitude":"51.560030","longitude":"0.435394","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"139","title":"King Edward VIII Scout Park \"Riffhams\"","description":"King Edward VIII Scout Park, also known as Riffhams is a 4 hectare wooded site adjacent to over 100 hectares of National Trust land near Chelmsford, Essex. We are located only a few miles from the site of the 2007 World Jamboree at Hylands Park. The site comprises of coppiced and standing woodland mainly chestnut, hornbeam and oak. There are a number of camping areas suitable for both group and patrol camping, water taps are conveniently located around the site.\n\nA hut with kitchen facilities is available and is ideal for centralised catering and wet weather shelter. Cooking rings, gas and basic utensils are provided. The toilet block has the usual facilities plus a disabled toilet and a shower. The site is great for traditional camping and backwoods \/ survival activities.\n\nPioneering poles, and orienteering course and Nature Trail are available for hire.\n\nThere is plenty to do in the local area and London is only 30mins by train.\n\nRiffhams is a great based for D of E training and is situated an ideal expedition distance from Prances camp site at Wickham Bishops.","contact":"Nigel Wood: nigel.d.wood@bt.com Tel:01245 467803\/07708 178850 ","link":"http:\/\/www.essexscouts.org.uk\/activitycentres\/riffhams","lastupdated":"2012-05-03","latitude":"51.726650","longitude":"0.573598","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"140","title":"Prances ","description":"Prances is owned by Maldon & East Essex District Scouts, and is named after the lady that donated the land to the district. Based in the heart of Wickham Bishops, it is a small but friendly site. There is plenty of room for campers and an excellent backwoods area for those that fancy sleeping under the stars.  The site is also suitable for Patrol Camps and the surrounding area is ideal for hiking\n\nThe campsite shop is well stocked with uniforms, accessories and souvenirs. There is an open air chapel and a campfire circle available for use by all. Peter Church Lodge is a large modern building, which is also available for use. This comprises of a large hall (approx 9m x 12m), kitchen with serving hatch, lobby area, store room, toilet facilities with hot showers, and the loft. The Bill Meeham loft, and the toilet facilities are also available for hire separately from the main building.\n\nCampers now have the benefit of a new purpose built toilet & shower block. With the advantage of having underfloor heating, it also provides excellent disabled facilities, including a wet room, and a utility room offering fridge and freezer.\n\nIn addition to the original camping area we now have an extra 3.8 acres of open grass field site for use as a camping area and general activities\/play area.\n\nAlso available for hire, are camp beds for indoor use, and chairs, tables and forms for outdoor use.\n","contact":"prancesscout@btinternet.com","link":"http:\/\/www.prances.org.uk","lastupdated":"2011-10-13","latitude":"51.776747","longitude":"0.678029","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"141","title":"Skreens Park","description":"Skreens Park Activity Centre is a 55 acre park providing activities and accomodation for young people. There are 25 allocated camping areas around the park, with two toilet\/wash blocks (one with ladies and gents showers) fitted with facilities for the disabled. There is also a wet weather barn. The site is available to Scouts and Guides throughout the year. There is a 3 acre lake and an open-air chapel and a log-seated campfire circle. The camp shop sells sweets, drinks, T-shirts, sweatshirts, badges and souvenirs of all kinds. Between November and March arrangements must be made at time of booking for shop opening hours. BUILDINGS: The Tinley Centre - A brick built centre that sleeps 36, available without heating (May to September), or with heating (October to April).  The Leaman Centre - A brick built centre that sleeps 30, available without heating (May to September), or with heating (October to April). The Warren Centre - A timber built centre that sleeps 36, and has no heating and no showers\n\nAll buildings are equiped with kitchens, dining rooms, washing and toilet facilities. Gas and Electricity are included within the Hire charge. There is also a 30x20 marquee available.\n\nACTIVITIES \n\nAround 20 activities are available to Scouts & Guides. Air Rifles - 4 Rifles per session (Approx number 20 per hour) Archery - 4 Bows per session (Approx number 20 per hour) Abseiling - 1 Rope\/Drop per session (Approx number 10 per hour) Canoes - 5 Canoes per session (Approx number 20 per hour) Cork Guns - 4 Guns per session (Approx number 20 per hour) Pedal Carts - 4 Carts per session (Approx number 20 per hour) Pond Dipping - 10 nets per session (Approx number 30 per hour) Pioneering Raft Building Volleyball, Badminton, Pre-planned hikes, Orienteering & Nature Trail are also available at no charge. At the end of 2011 saw the new caving simulator introduced with approx 720' of tunneling. Skreens Park Activity Centre is managed by Essex Scouts. Completed booking forms and a deposit should be sent to the Activity Centre Manager with cheques payable to \u2018Essex County Scout Council' Activity sessions should be booked in advance and confirmation should be raised with the team about Instructor availability and the use of your own equipment. Current qualification certificates must be produced before any activity is undertaken.","contact":"info@skreenspark.org.uk","link":"http:\/\/www.skreenspark.org.uk\/","lastupdated":"2012-10-13","latitude":"51.747735","longitude":"0.351590","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"142","title":"Cherrywood","description":"Cherrywood is a relatively new campsite, located to the west of Thurrock. It has easy access from the M25 and Dartford river crossing, and to Lakeside shopping centre.\n\nCherrywood is ideal for bivouac practice and orienteering. The site is made up of two camping areas: one of five acres, and one of one acre in a clearing in the woods with a Log cabin. The Log cabin sleeps 10 youths plus 4 adults, and has catering facilities for 24. It consists of a hall (5m square), kitchen, toilet, and 2 bunk rooms, each sleeping 2. There are also picnic tables available for use. The clearing in the woods has room for 6 patrol tents, and can be used together with the Log cabin.\n\nThe site also has a cloth badge for sale.\n\nFacilities:\n\nModern toilet block for male, female and handicapped persons\nHot\/cold showers\nLarge car park\nCamp fire circle\n15 point orienteering course with instructor.\nBivouac facilities\nArchery with instructor\nWater activities and climbing wall are available off site, about 4 miles away","contact":"01375 891445 ","link":"http:\/\/www.essexscouts.org.uk\/activitycentres\/cherrywood","lastupdated":"2011-10-13","latitude":"51.486037","longitude":"0.247709","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"143","title":"Ark Lane","description":"Situated on 3 acres of beautiful semi-wooded land, Ark Lane has 2 camping fields, 2 buildings, fire bases incluidng a main campfire circle. The site is ideal for camps for all ages, and lends itself to activities including scoutcraft, backwoods skills, wide games, field games, skills training, conservation and environmental projects.\n\nBuildings\nThe 2 buildings are ideal for all types of meetings for both young people and adults, including training, as well as Nights Away with your young people (however the buildings do not have bunks so users will need to bring something to lie on). Both buildings are heated and are fully equiped with tables and chairs and kitchen facilities.\n\nEquipment & Other Facilities\nWe have a wealth of camping and cooking equipment which may be borrowed (for a donation) for use either at the site or away from site. The site\u2019s car park can accommodate approximately 25 cars and a further 15 cars if one of the camp sites is used. We also have amain campfire circle aswell as several fire bases located around the site, and we now have pioneering equipment available too.\n\nSite Visits \/ Service Team\nWe invite all Leaders in Scouting and Guiding and other youth organisations to come and visit the site at any time - contact the Site Warden to make arrangements. Our Service Team meets approximately once a month and we always welcome new people of all ages who would like to help out around the site or for Groups who would like to embark on a service project. Please contact the Site Warden for further details or to make arrangements","contact":"01268 777785 ","link":"http:\/\/www.essexscouts.org.uk\/activitycentres\/arklane","lastupdated":"2011-10-13","latitude":"51.582137","longitude":"0.673825","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"144","title":"Glenny Wood","description":"An ideal site for all ages offering traditional Scouting opportunities combined with more modern activities and safety requirements","contact":"","link":"http:\/\/www.avonscouts.org.uk\/activity-adventure\/campsites-and-activity-centres\/glenny-wood-campsite\/","lastupdated":"2012-10-23","latitude":"51.457373","longitude":"-2.759484","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"147","title":"Cricket Campsite","description":"District Campsite and activity centre","contact":"","link":"http:\/\/www.isdsc.org.uk","lastupdated":"2013-04-28","latitude":"50.898724","longitude":"-1.299299","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"148","title":"Stanford Scout Camp Site","description":"Crawley District Scouts","contact":"Julie Hole - StanfordScoutCampSite@gmail.com","link":"http:\/\/sites.google.com\/site\/stanfordscoutcampsite\/","lastupdated":"2013-06-15","latitude":"51.086887","longitude":"-0.210301","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"151","title":"Adamswell Scout Campsite","description":"Adamswell Scout Campsite - owned by Royal Tunbridge Wells Scout District","contact":"www.adamswell.org.uk","link":"http:\/\/www.adamswell.org.uk","lastupdated":"2011-10-24","latitude":"51.120595","longitude":"0.210851","categoryid":"1"},{"facilityid":"152","title":"Bramhope  Scout Campsite","description":"Bramhope Scout Campsite is situated some 8 Miles NNW of Leeds, and half a mile West of Bramhope Village. The campsite has fift